03855nam a22005055i 9780773568914DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20002000xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735689147 a10.1515/97807735689142doi  a(DE-B1597)655625  a(OCoLC)741349792  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aJS78 ǂb S26 2000eb 7aPOL0200002bisacsh04a320.8/591 aSancton, Andrew, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMerger Mania /cAndrew Sancton. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2000] 4c©2000  a1 online resource (184 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tSummary -- tIntroduction -- tMunicipal Amalgamation in the United States, 1854-1942 -- tThe Era of Big Government: The 1960s and 1970s -- tThe Decline of the Consolidationist Movement in the United States, the Emergence of "Public Choice," and the "New Regionalism" -- tAmalgamations in the 1990s -- tToronto'S Megacity1 -- tMore Change in Ontario: Ottawa, Hamilton, Sudbury, and Toronto (Again) -- tConclusion -- tBibliography0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOutside the United States, forced municipal mergers were a popular policy in many European countries and Canadian provinces during the 1960s and 1970s. The city of Laval, just north of Montreal, and the "unicity" of Winnipeg owe their origins to this period - both amalgamations failed to meet their original objectives. Despite the emergence of "public choice" theory - which justifies municipal fragmentation on market principles - some politicians and public servants in the 1990s have continued to advocate municipal amalgamations as a means of reducing public expenditure, particularly in Ontario. In Merger Mania Andrew Sancton demonstrates that this approach has generally not saved money. He examines the history of amalgamation, as well as studying recent forced municipal mergers in Halifax, Toronto, Ottawa, Hamilton, and Sudbury. In the concluding chapter he examines the case for municipal amalgamation on the Island of Montreal and argues that those who would abolish locally elected municipal councils are obligated to explain very carefully - especially in light of evidence to the contrary - exactly why they think such drastic measures are necessary. A compelling examination of a timely issue, Merger Mania is a must-read for anyone interested in the politics of city governments.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / American Government / State.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356891440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773568914423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773568914/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles